          "explanation": "This is a case of Lambe Eaton syndrome occurring in the setting of small cell carcinoma of lung. RNS study shows incremental response which goes in or of Lambe Eaton syndrome (LEMS). Lambe-Eaton syndrome Presents with proximal muscle weakness Ptosis and diplopia Absent DTRs. Autonomic dysfunction Autoantibodies directed against P/Q-type calcium channels at the motor nerve terminals Found in 85% of LEMS patients. These impair the release of ACh from nerve terminals. In older adults, most LEMS is associated with malignancy. Most common malignancy associated is commonly small-cell lung cancer (SCLC)",
