        {
          "id": "medmcqa-7a95c72c-ecb7-4a8b-add5-4c897fc7800d",
          "text": "A drug that binds to receptor at a site distinct from the active site and alters the affinity of the receptor for the endogenous ligand is a:",
          "options": [
            {
              "id": "opt-1",
              "text": "Competitive antagonist"
            },
            {
              "id": "opt-2",
              "text": "Inverse agonist"
            },
            {
              "id": "opt-3",
              "text": "Partial agonist"
            },
            {
              "id": "opt-4",
              "text": "Allosteric modulator"
            }
          ],
          "correctOptionId": "opt-3",
          "explanation": "Ref. KDT. Page. 59\nCompetitive (equilibrium type –Allosteric modulator)\n\nThe drug being structurally similar competes with the normal substrate for the catalytic binding site of the enzyme\nThey increase the kM but the Vmax remains unchanged\n\nExamples:\n\nPhysostigmine and neostigmine compete with acetylcholine for cholinesterase.\nSulfonamides compete with P ABA for bacterial folate synthetase.  \nMoclobemide competes with catecholamines for monoamine oxidase-A (MAO-A).  \nCaptopril competes with angiotensin 1 for angiotensin converting enzyme (ACE)."
        },
        {
          "id": "medmcqa-dda6fa10-24de-47b2-8bf1-af8fa36f0e83",
          "text": "Multiple sclerosis is characterized by all EXCEPT -",
          "options": [
            {
              "id": "opt-1",
              "text": "Demyelination"
            },
            {
              "id": "opt-2",
              "text": "Grey-tan plaques in the white matter"
            },
            {
              "id": "opt-3",
              "text": "Increased protein concentration in CSF"
            },
            {
              "id": "opt-4",
              "text": "Oligodendrocytes"
            }
          ],
          "correctOptionId": "opt-3",
          "explanation": "i.e. (Oligodendrocytes): (884-Harsh Mohan 6th) (1310-1312-Robbins & Cotran 8th)MULTIPLE SCLEROSIS - is an autoimmune demyelinating disorder characterized by distinct episodes of neurologic deficits separated in time, attributable to white matter lesions that are separated in space*Pathologic hallmark is the presence of many scattered discrete areas of demyelination termed plaques**MORPHOLOGIC FEATURES*Grossly - plaque appears as grey-pink swollen sharply defined usually bilaterally symmetric areas in the white matter*Microscopically - according to the age of the plaque1. Inactive enlarging plaque, the histologic features are an accumulation of lymphocytes and macrophages around venules and at the plaque margin where demyelination is occurring. In addition, there is a loss of oligodendrocytes and presence of reactive astrocytes with numerous lipid-laden macrophages (microglia) in the plaque. The axons in the plaque are generally intact.2. In old inactive plaque - there is no perivascular inflammatory cell infiltrate and nearly total absence of oligodendrocytes. Demyelination in the plaque area is complete as there is an only limited regeneration of myelin gliosis is well developed but astrocytes are less prominent. Some axonal loss may be present."
        }
